{"title_page": "2011 in politics", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=January 2017}}\n{{yearbox\n| in?=in politics\n| cp=20th century\n| c=21st century\n| cf=22nd century\n| yp1=2008\n| yp2=2009\n| yp3=2009\n| year=2011\n| ya1=2012\n| ya2=2013\n| ya3=2014\n| dp3=1970s\n| dp2=1980s\n| dp1=1990s\n| d=2010\u20132019{{!}}2010s\n| dn1=2010s\n| dn2=2020s\n| dn3=2030s\n|}}\n\n{{see also|2010s political history}}\n\nThese are some of the notable events relating to [[politics]] in 2011.\n\n==Events==\n===January===\n\n[[File:Deepwater Horizon oil spill - May 24, 2010 - with locator.jpg|thumb|Deepwater Horizon oil spill]]\n[[File:Tahrir Square during 8 February 2011.jpg|thumb|Tahrir Square, Egypt, 8 February 2011]]\n* January 1 \u2013 [[Brazil]] inaugurates first female President, [[Dilma Rousseff]]{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n* January 6 \u2013 Investigation continues into [[BP oil spill]] off Gulf of Mexico<ref>{{cite news|title=US oil spill: 'Bad management' led to BP disaster|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-12124830|agency=BBC|date=6 January 2011}}</ref>\n* January 8 \u2013 American congresswoman [[Gabrielle Giffords]] [[2011 Tucson shooting|shot]] in [[Arizona]]{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n* January 14 \u2013 Amid the [[2010\u20132011 Tunisian protests]], long-time president [[Zine El Abidine Ben Ali]] dissolved the government, and flees the country due to [[Zine El Abidine Ben Ali#Ousted from the presidency|opposition and military intervention]], Tunisian PM steps in as interim President{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n* January 16 \u2013 Former President [[Jean-Claude Duvalier]] returns to Haiti 25 years after being overthrown<ref>{{cite news|title='Baby Doc' Duvalier returns to Haiti from exile|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-11943820|agency=BBC|date=16 January 2011}}</ref>\n* January 17 \u2013 Reports of [[self-immolation]] spread across Africa<ref>{{cite news|last1=Levs|first1=Josh|title=Self-immolation reports spread through north Africa |url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/01/17/tunisia.self.immolation/|agency=CNN|date=17 January 2011}}</ref>\n* January 17 \u2013 Allegations of sexual misconduct committed by [[Silvio Berlusconi|Italian Prime Minister Berlusconi]] grow<ref>{{cite news|title='Italy PM Silvio Berlusconi prostitute allegations widen|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-12209110|agency=BBC|date=17 January 2011}}</ref>\n* January 18 \u2013 Obama hosts Chinese [[President Hu]] at private dinner<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama hosts China's Hu at rare private White House meal|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-pacific-12212843|agency=BBC|date=18 January 2011}}</ref>\n* January 20 \u2013 New Tunisian government lifts bans on previously outlawed political groups, frees political prisoners<ref>{{cite news|title=Tunisian government lifts ban on political groups|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/01/20/tunisia.protests/|agency=CNN|date=20 January 2011}}</ref>\n* January 22 \u2013 Algerians defy ban on government protests, protest in capital<ref>{{cite news|title=Algerians defy ban to protest government|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/01/22/algeria.protest/|agency=CNN|date=22 January 2011}}</ref>\n* January 23 \u2013 [[Green Party of Ireland|The Green Party of Ireland]] pulls out of Irish government, forcing early elections<ref>{{cite news|title=Greens pull out of crumbling Irish government|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/europe/01/23/ireland.politics/|agency=CNN|date=23 January 2011}}</ref>\n* January 24 \u2013 Suicide bomb detonated at [[Domodedovo airport]] in Russia<ref>{{cite news|title=Moscow bombing: Carnage at Russia's Domodedovo airport\n|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-12268662|agency=BBC|date=24 January 2011}}</ref>\n* January 24 \u2013 Protests in Yemeni capital [[Sana, Yemen|Sanaa]], spurned on by changes in Tunisia<ref>{{cite news|title=Protesters march in attempt to force Yemen's president out|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/01/27/yemen.protests/|agency=CNN|date=24 January 2011}}</ref>\n* January 27 \u2013 Egyptian opposition leader and Nobel peace laureate [[Mohamed ElBaradei]] return to Cairo amid political unrest{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n* January 29 \u2013 [[Egyptian revolution of 2011|Protest in Egypt]] continue, spurned on by reports from Tunisia, protesters believe [[Housni Mubarak|President]] will soon step down<ref>{{cite news|title=Defiance on Cairo streets as protesters 'lose fear'|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/01/29/egypt.protest.sat/|agency=CNN|date=29 January 2011}}</ref>\n* January 30 \u2013 In a preliminary vote, 99% of South Sudan votes to split from the North, brought about by the [[Comprehensive Peace Agreement|2005 peace agreement]] which ended two decades of war<ref>{{cite news|title=Complete preliminary results show 99% vote to split in Southern Sudan |url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/01/22/sudan.referendum.results/|agency=CNN|date=30 January 2011}}</ref>\n* January 30 \u2013 Protesters in London march against [[President Mubarak|Egyptian President Mubarak]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Protesters around the world march against Egypt's Mubarak|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/01/29/egypt.world.protests/|agency=CNN|date=30 January 2011}}</ref>\n* January 31 \u2013 Egyptian army rules out the use of force against the thousands of protesters across the country<ref>{{cite news|title=Egypt protests: Army rules out the use of force|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-12330169|agency=BBC|date=31 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n\n[[File:King Abdullah portrait.jpg|thumb|King Abdullah of Jordan]]\n\n* February 1 \u2013 [[King Abdullah II]], King of Jordan, dismisses the government of Jordan, appoints new PM with orders to implement political reform<ref>{{cite news|title=Jordan's king dismisses government, appoints new PM|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/02/01/jordan.government/|agency=CNN|date=1 February 2011}}</ref>\n* February 1 \u2013 [[President Mubarak|Egyptian President Mubarak]] says he will not run again after his current term ends, protesters do not capitulate<ref>{{cite news|title=Mubarak says he won't run again; protesters say it's not enough|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/02/01/egypt.protests/|agency=CNN|date=1 February 2011}}</ref>\n* February 3 \u2013 Gunfire in central Cairo, as pro-Mubarak protesters clash with anti-Mubarak protesters<ref>{{cite news|title=New gunfire erupts in central Cairo|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/02/02/egypt.protests/|agency=CNN|date=3 February 2011}}</ref>\n* February 4 \u2013 Crowds grow in [[Tahrir Square]] as protesters rally to celebrate day of departure<ref>{{cite news|title=Egypt protests: Many at Cairo 'day of departure' rally|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-12362826|agency=BBC|date=4 February 2011}}</ref>\n* February 7 \u2013 Egyptian government raises pay of public sector workers by 15% in attempt to quell protests<ref>{{cite news|title=Egypt unrest: Public-sector pay rise but protests go on|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-12387181|agency=BBC|date=7 February 2011}}</ref>\n* February 8 \u2013 North Korea and South Korea initiate military talks after year long hiatus<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kitchen|first1=Michael|title=North, South Korea in military talks after hiatus|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/north-south-korea-in-military-talks-after-hiatus-2011-02-07|agency=Market Watch|date=8 February 2011}}</ref>\n* February 11 \u2013 Amid the [[2011 Egyptian revolution]], long-time president [[Hosni Mubarak]] resigns{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n* February 12 \u2013 Egypt's military leaders, currently in control of country, pledge to uphold all existing international treaties<ref>{{cite news|title=Egypt military authorities 'to respect all treaties'|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-12440138|agency=BBC|date=13 February 2011}}</ref>\n* February 13 \u2013 Egypt's military, currently in control of country, dissolve parliament and suspend constitution, stating they will control the country for 6 months or until elections can be held<ref>{{cite news|title=Egypt's military dissolves Parliament, suspends constitution|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/02/13/egypt.revolution/|agency=CNN|date=13 February 2011}}</ref>\n* February 13 \u2013 Italian women stage anti [[Silvio Berlusconi|Berlusconi]] demonstrations, in wake of allegations of sexual misconduct<ref>{{cite news|title=Italian women hold anti-Berlusconi demonstrations|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-12442833|agency=BBC|date=13 February 2011}}</ref>\n* February 14 \u2013 Large protests around Algerian capital, protesters call for democratic leadership<ref>{{cite news|title=Protesters, police clash in Algerian capital|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/02/12/algeria.protest/|agency=CNN|date=14 February 2011}}</ref>\n* February 16 \u2013 Protests erupt in Benghazi, Libya<ref>{{cite news|title=Libya protests: Second city Benghazi hit by violence|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-12477275|agency=BBC|date=16 February 2011}}</ref>\n* February 16 \u2013 Police and pro democracy protesters clash] in [[Manama]] Bahrain<ref>{{cite news|title=At least 2 people dead after police move on protesters in Bahrain|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/02/16/bahrain.protests/|agency=CNN|date=16 February 2011}}</ref>\n* February 20 \u2013 Clashes across the city of Benghazi leave 200 dead and 900 injured<ref>{{cite news|title=Libya unrest: Scores killed in Benghazi 'massacre'|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-12517327|agency=BBC|date=20 February 2011}}</ref>\n* February 20 \u2013 Security forces shut down protests in [[Tehran]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Security forces push back on Iranian protesters|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/02/20/iran.protests/|agency=CNN|date=20 February 2011}}</ref>\n* February 22 \u2013 Libyan leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]] refuses to stand down amid wide spread protests<ref>{{cite news|title=Libya protests: Defiant Gaddafi refuses to quit|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-12544624|agency=BBC|date=22 February 2011}}</ref>\n* February 25 \u2013 [[Barack Obama]] announces American sanctions against Gaddafi's Libya<ref>{{cite news|title=Libya: Barack Obama announces Gaddafi sanctions|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-12585949|agency=BBC|date=25 February 2011}}</ref>\n* February 26 \u2013 [[UN Security Council]] unanimously approves sanctions against Libya<ref>{{cite news|title=Libya: UN Security Council votes sanctions on Gaddafi|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-12589434|agency=BBC|date=26 February 2011}}</ref>\n* February 27 \u2013 Unrest in Libya spark border crisis, as civilians attempting to flee violence cross into neighboring countries<ref>{{cite news|title=Libya unrest sparks refugee crisis at Tunisia border|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-12591935|agency=BBC|date=27 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n* March 2 \u2013 Pakistani minority minister [[Shahbaz Bhatti]] killed in ambush in Islamabad<ref>{{cite news|title=Pakistan Minorities Minister Shahbaz Bhatti shot dead|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-south-asia-12617562|agency=BBC|date=2 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:SH-60B helicopter flies over Sendai.jpg|thumb|Helicopter flies over Sendai, Japan]]\n* March 4 \u2013 Libyan security forces force protesters from Tripoli, Gaddafi's stronghold<ref>{{cite news|title=Libya: Protests hit Gaddafi stronghold of Tripoli|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-12644435|agency=BBC|date=4 March 2011}}</ref>\n* March 5 \u2013 [[Saudi Arabia]] imposes ban on protests<ref>{{cite news|title=Saudi Arabia imposes ban on all protests|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-12656744|agency=BBC|date=5 March 2011}}</ref>\n* March 9 \u2013 [[Wisconsin]] bans collective bargaining for state's public employees<ref>{{cite news|title=Wis. governor 